05888nam a22006975i 9780822379263DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19941994ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223792637 a10.1515/97808223792632doi  a(DE-B1597)552162  a(OCoLC)1125874702  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE59.W9bW75 1993 7aFOR0310002bisacsh04a49700aWriting Without Words :bAlternative Literacies in Mesoamerica and the Andes /cElizabeth Hill Boone, Walter D. Mignolo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1994] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b54 b&w photographs, 27 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Writing and Recording Knowledge -- tLiteracy among the Pre-Columbian Maya: A Comparative Perspective -- tAztec Pictorial Histories: Records without Words -- tVoicing the Painted Image: A Suggestion for Reading the Reverse of the Codex Cospi -- tThe Text in the Body, the Body in the Text: The Embodied Sign in Mixtec Writing -- tHearing the Echoes of Verbal Art in Mixtec Writing -- tMexican Codices, Maps, and Lienzos as Social Contracts -- tPrimers for Memory: Cartographic Histories and Nahua Identity -- tRepresentation in the Sixteenth Century and the Colonial Image of the Inca -- tSigns and Their Transmission: The Question of the Book in the New World -- tObject and Alphabet: Andean Indians and Documents in the Colonial Period -- tAfterword: Writing and Recorded Knowledge in Colonial and Postcolonial Situations -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of writing, or so the standard story goes, is an ascending process, evolving toward the alphabet and finally culminating in the "full writing" of recorded speech. Writing without Words challenges this orthodoxy, and with it widespread notions of literacy and dominant views of art and literature, history and geography. Asking how knowledge was encoded and preserved in Pre-Columbian and early colonial Mesoamerican cultures, the authors focus on systems of writing that did not strive to represent speech. Their work reveals the complicity of ideology in the history of literacy, and offers new insight into the history of writing.The contributors--who include art historians, anthropologists, and literary theorists--examine the ways in which ancient Mesoamerican and Andean peoples conveyed meaning through hieroglyphic, pictorial, and coded systems, systems inseparable from the ideologies they were developed to serve. We see, then, how these systems changed with the European invasion, and how uniquely colonial writing systems came to embody the post-conquest American ideologies. The authors also explore the role of these early systems in religious discourse and their relation to later colonial writing.Bringing the insights from Mesoamerica and the Andes to bear on a fundamental exchange among art history, literary theory, semiotics, and anthropology, the volume reveals the power contained in the medium of writing.Contributors. Elizabeth Hill Boone, Tom Cummins, Stephen Houston, Mark B. King, Dana Leibsohn, Walter D. Mignolo, John Monaghan, John M. D. Pohl, Joanne Rappaport, Peter van der Loo  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aIndian art. 0aIndians of MexicoxLanguagesxWriting. 0aIndiansxLanguagesxWriting. 0aWritingxHistory. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Native American Languages.2bisacsh1 aBoone, Elizabeth Hill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeibsohn, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill Boone, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRa